  "datePublished": "2026-03-04",
  "description": "Popularity effects arise when certain species or observations receive disproportionate attention, driving more uploads and IDs for those taxa while others lag.\n¶Indicators High ID throughput for birds and charismatic mammals. Slow or absent review for cryptic insects, fungi, or plants. Comment and identification backlogs in taxon groups with few experts. Heavy reliance on computer vision suggestions for common taxa. ¶Mitigation practices Prioritize understudied taxa in your own observations. Identify within groups that need more reviewer attention. Provide explanatory comments instead of quick agreement clicks for difficult taxa. ¶What goes wrong if you do this poorly Popularity-driven data become self-reinforcing: common taxa get better data, while scarce taxa remain poorly documented. This can distort perceived biodiversity patterns and research priorities.\n",
  "name": "Failure mode: popularity effects",
  "publisher": {
